== Q: What time do I need to get there? Can I walk-in late? ==

A: If you are new to Python and/or need help with installation issues, we suggest that you come in a few minutes early. This will help the volunteers keep you in pace with the rest of the group. That said, you can walk-in later but if you are too late you will miss out on interesting learning bits as the dojos will not be meeting for more than 3 hours each week, albeit individuals may stay back to continue working until the host closes for the day.


== Q: Will there be any lectures, discussions, talks, etc.. ? ==

A: Not in the near future. Depending on the situation, we will split into smaller groups, or pair-program to help each other understand something new. That means the person sitting next to you can be your teacher or you can ping someone else who is not busy for help. 

In future, we may think about (occasionally) hosting guest speakers interested in conducting workshops and/or sprints. If you are a core-dev for any Python package and you want to conduct workshops to introduce newbies to bug-squashing, feel free to talk to us.


== Q: Are there any teachers and do you give any certificates? ==

A: No, and NO - we definitely do NOT hand out pieces of paper. We are not an Institute, nor a commercial entity in the training or education business and dont do commercial certifications. Pyladies a volunteer effort and we have no teachers, only facilitators - [https://github.com/xenathewarrior Anu], [https://github.com/suni0847 Sunita], [https://github.com/svaksha Svaksha] and other fellow attendees, who will be around to help each other learn Python. Yeah, the facilitators, like you are learners too!


== Q: I don't own a laptop. Can I attend the Dojo? ==

A: Folks that dont have laptops are also welcome - at CIS we cant provide machines to work on but you can watch others code, ask questions, learn by pair programming, etc.. If we use the Thoughworks office as our venue, they might be able to arrange for spare machines (subject to confirmation). 


== Q: I don't know how to code. Can I attend the Dojo? But, I dont know "xyz"? ==

A: You are welcome to attend if you are willing to invest the time and energy to learn Python. Its OK to *not* know something so long as you want to learn how to code. Nobody will mock you for not groking Python decorators, or publicly saying “I dont know that”. All Pyladies events are bound by the [http://www.python.org/psf/codeofconduct/ Python-CoC], in addition to which we expect all attendees to follow our [http://www.pyladies.com/CodeOfConduct/ Code of Conduct].


== Q: I dont have a CS degree / I'm not an Engineer, can I learn to code? ==

A: A piece of paper should not limit your potential, so if you can put in the effort to learn Python, then you can definitely learn to code. We are mere catalysts that provide a free space, wifi, and like-minded Pythonistas, with you putting in the hard work to become a good programmer.


